            <fr:title text="Jordan algebra">Jordan algebra</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be a field. A <html:dfn>Jordan algebra</html:dfn> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is a nonassociative algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> whose multiplication satisfies:</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li>commutative: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[xy=yx]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>Jordan identity: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(xy)(xx)=x(y(xx))]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
            <html:p>Note that Springer and Veldkamp's <fr:link href="/veldkamp-2000-octonions/" title="Octonions, Jordan Algebras, and Exceptional Groups" uri="http://localhost:8000/veldkamp-2000-octonions/" display-uri="veldkamp-2000-octonions" type="local">Octonions, Jordan Algebras, and Exceptional Groups</fr:link> (remark 5.1.7, pg 122) note that the character of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {char}(J)\neq  2]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
